Force fields.

A force field is a barrier that pulses on and off on a timer, dangerous one moment and passable the next. While it's on, the field is a wall of energy: stepping into it hurts the player and throws them back out. While it's off, it's nothing at all, and the player can walk straight through. The rhythm is the whole point — a force field turns a doorway or a corridor into a timing puzzle, where the player has to watch the beat and cross during the gaps. Force fields come in a single-tile form and a ranged area that fills a whole rectangle.

How a force field works.

A force field fills a single tile or a rectangular area and cycles between two states, switching on its interval: it spends the interval on, then the interval off, then on again, forever. The on and off cues play as it flips so the player can hear the rhythm. While the field is off, it has no effect and the player passes through freely.

While the field is on, entering its tile or area triggers it: the player takes damage reduced by their defence, and is bounced back the way they came so they can't simply push through. A raised shield takes the damage in the player's place, wearing the shield down instead, but the player is still knocked back. Because the field repels as well as wounds, the way past is never to force it — it's to wait for the off phase and walk through cleanly. On 3d maps a ranged force field fills every height level between its minimum and maximum z.

Force field fields.

The force field form takes the following:

Build mode. Single for one exact tile, or ranged for a rectangular area. Single is the default.

Coordinates. For a single force field, an x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the one tile it covers. For a ranged force field, a minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangle it fills.

Attack. The damage the field deals when the player enters it while it's on, before the player's defence is subtracted.

Speed. The number of milliseconds the field stays on and, equally, the number it stays off, so a smaller number makes it flicker faster between dangerous and safe.

Force field sound (a folder name from the force field sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the on cue, the off cue, and the hit clip played when the field catches the player. Pick none for a silent force field.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the force field sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the highlighted theme's hit clip, hold control and press N to hear its on cue, and hold control and press O to hear its off cue.

Authoring force fields by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a force field is written under the name force_field. A single one is force_field x y damage speed forcetype, and on 3d maps a z follows the y: force_field x y z damage speed forcetype. A ranged one is force_field minx maxx miny maxy damage speed forcetype, and on 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: force_field minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz damage speed forcetype. Both forms share the one force_field name — the line is read as ranged when it carries the extra coordinates. The damage and speed are numbers, and the force field sound must match a force field sounds folder name or the word none.
